## Additional Color Customizations

### Status Bar Colors

In `view.go` (around line 180):

```go
// Default
statusBar := lipgloss.NewStyle().
    Foreground(lipgloss.Color("252")).
    Background(lipgloss.Color("236"))

// Gruvbox
statusBar := lipgloss.NewStyle().
    Foreground(lipgloss.Color("223")).
    Background(lipgloss.Color("237"))
```

### Border Colors

In `render_preview.go` (around line 100):

```go
// Default
BorderForeground(lipgloss.Color("39"))  // Cyan

// Custom
BorderForeground(lipgloss.Color("141"))  // Purple
BorderForeground(lipgloss.Color("76"))   // Green
BorderForeground(lipgloss.Color("214"))  // Orange
```

### Context Menu Colors

In `context_menu.go` (around line 440):

```go
// Selected item
selectedStyle := lipgloss.NewStyle().
    Background(lipgloss.Color("39")).   // Change this
    Foreground(lipgloss.Color("0"))

// Menu background
normalStyle := lipgloss.NewStyle().
    Background(lipgloss.Color("236"))   // Change this
```

## Testing Your Colors

1. Edit `styles.go`
2. Rebuild: `go build -o tfe`
3. Run TFE in your terminal
4. Check readability in different lighting conditions

## Tips

- Use high contrast for readability
- Test with your terminal's color scheme
- Consider both dark and light terminal backgrounds
- Avoid similar colors for folders/files (hard to distinguish)
- Keep selected items clearly visible

## Files Modified

- `styles.go` (main color definitions)
- `view.go` (status bar, toolbar)
- `render_preview.go` (borders)
- `context_menu.go` (menu colors)

Rebuild after changes: `go build -o tfe`
